    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e10ad494_045f9b29",
        "filename": "minijail0_cli.c",
        "patchSetId": 12
      },
      "lineNbr": 1009,
      "author": {
        "id": 1628636
      },
      "writtenOn": "2022-01-14T15:16:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The idea here was that if a user specifies --env-reset after --env-add, then they might be confused, because any --env-add appearing before an --env-reset will be useless.\n\nIndeed the ordering of the options have a meaning in this case, and having some --env-add before an --env-reset is almost entirely likely to be an error.\n\nWhat do you think? Shall we still implement it and not warn the user that what they\u0027ll have is probably not what they intended?",
      "parentUuid": "ab20805a_311c4dfd",
      "revId": "4669fd0b52eed074aabd8eec37fffad1475bacbe",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d3d1ab2e_e85bab61",
        "filename": "minijail0_cli.c",
        "patchSetId": 12
      },
      "lineNbr": 1009,
      "author": {
        "id": 1040868
      },
      "writtenOn": "2022-01-24T22:07:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "the behavior you describe i think is entirely expected and normal.  CLI options are basically levers to a state machine.  having ones that clobber previous ones makes it easier to test and easier to write shell scripts.  this philosophy isn\u0027t specific to minijail.\n\ni agree that a user doing `minijail0 --env-add --env-add --env-reset --env-add` doesn\u0027t make much sense.  but if it were written in a script with overrides and args coming from multiple sources, or if i\u0027m doing quick testing on the CLI, it can be helpful.\n\nsay i see a program run and it fails.  i copy \u0026 paste that long command line into my shell and start experimenting.  i want to make sure the env is in a certain state, so i tack on the --env-reset --env-add options to the end.  now it\u0027s how i expect it.  i don\u0027t have to scan the full command line to figure out which ones i have to delete to make the CLI parser happy.\n\nminijail itself doesn\u0027t have too many on/off options that currently fall into this bucket.  but if you look at other tools, it\u0027s easy to recognize the pattern.  consider ls/grep/etc... that have --color options.  if the user has an alias like `alias ls\u003d\u0027ls --color\u0027`, and then they run `ls --color\u003dnever`, should that issue an error ?",
      "parentUuid": "e10ad494_045f9b29",
      "revId": "4669fd0b52eed074aabd8eec37fffad1475bacbe",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
